\textbf{Project Title:} \emph{LeafLogic} (AI-Powered Plant Disease
Diagnostic System)

\textbf{1. Project Overview}

\textbf{Scope}

LeafLogic is a cross-platform mobile application (Android/iOS) designed
to bridge the gap between complex botanical science and everyday
gardening. The system leverages Flutter for the frontend and a
Python-based Machine Learning backend to provide instantaneous, on-site
disease diagnosis through image recognition. It is specifically scoped
to identify at least 15 distinct plant-disease pairs across five major
species, providing both a diagnosis and an organic treatment plan.

\textbf{Problem Statement}

In both domestic and large-scale agriculture, rapid identification of
plant pathology is critical for crop survival. Traditional diagnostic
methods, such as consulting physical encyclopedias or waiting for human
experts, are often too slow to prevent the rapid spread of pathogens.
There is a need for a high-speed, accessible tool that reduces
"time-to-treatment" for distressed plants.

\textbf{Objectives}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \textbf{Develop an Accessible Diagnostic Tool:} To create a
  functional, cross-platform mobile MVP (using Flutter) that allows
  users to easily photograph a distressed leaf and receive an
  instantaneous disease diagnosis.
\item
  \textbf{High Accuracy Identification:} Achieve 80\%+ accuracy in
  detecting common diseases like Rust, Powdery Mildew, and Blight.
\item
  \textbf{Educational Outreach:} Provide actionable, environmentally
  friendly treatment advice alongside the diagnosis.
\item
  \textbf{History Tracking:} Enable users to monitor plant health over
  time through a persistent digital log.
\item
  \textbf{Offline Functionality:} Ensure basic diagnostic capabilities
  in remote areas with poor cellular reception.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{System Limitations / Constraints}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \textbf{Species Limitation:} The initial MVP is constrained to five
  major plant species and 15 specific plant-disease pairs.
\item
  \textbf{Hardware Dependency:} Optimal performance requires a mobile
  device with a functional camera and enough processing power to run
  TFLite models.
\item
  \textbf{Not a Substitute for Lab Testing:} The app provides a
  preliminary diagnostic suggestion based on visual symptoms. It is not
  a substitute for professional laboratory testing and should be used as
  a guide, not a definitive, legally-binding diagnosis.
\item
  \textbf{Liability:} The project explicitly avoids "life-safety"
  liability by focusing on plant pathology rather than edibility.
\item
  \textbf{Storage:} High-resolution reference images and the full
  "Disease Encyclopedia" require an internet connection to access the
  cloud database.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{2. System Requirements}

\textbf{Functional Requirements (FR)}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \textbf{Image Capture:} The system must allow users to photograph a
  distressed leaf using an integrated camera module with an overlay
  guide.
\item
  \textbf{Positioning Assistance:} The system must display an on-screen
  guide or overlay within the camera module to assist the user in
  positioning the leaf correctly for optimal scanning.
\item
  \textbf{Image Pre-processing:} The system must pre-process the
  captured or selected image using OpenCV for noise reduction and
  segmentation before sending it to the ML model.
\item
  \textbf{AI Disease Analysis:} The system must utilize a trained CNN
  model (such as MobileNetV2 or ResNet-50) to analyze the image and
  identify the plant species and specific disease.
\item
  \textbf{Diagnostic Reporting:} The system must return and display a
  diagnosis result, including the identified disease name, the plant
  species, and a confidence score (e.g., 94\% Certainty).
\item
  \textbf{Treatment Recommendations:} The system must query its
  repository to display relevant, actionable treatment plans, including
  both organic and chemical options, based on the diagnosed disease.
\item
  \textbf{Automated Data Logging:} The system must automatically save
  every scan result, including the image, diagnosis, and date, to the
  user\textquotesingle s persistent history log.
\item
  \textbf{History Management:} The system must allow users to view,
  browse, and delete past scans from their localized or cloud-based
  history log to track treatment progress.
\item
  \textbf{Offline Diagnostics:} The system must function in a limited
  offline mode by using a locally stored TensorFlow Lite model to
  provide diagnoses when no internet connection is available.
\item
  \textbf{Backend Integration:} The system must communicate with a
  FastAPI backend to perform high-performance asynchronous diagnostic
  requests when an internet connection is active.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Non-Functional Requirements (NFR)}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \textbf{Performance:} The system should reduce time-to-treatment by
  80\% compared to manual methods, providing near-instantaneous results.
\item
  \textbf{Accuracy:} The diagnostic model must maintain a minimum of
  80\% accuracy.
\item
  \textbf{Usability:} The interface must be clean and "user-friendly"
  for non-expert gardeners.
\item
  \textbf{Portability:} The application must be cross-platform,
  functional on both Android and iOS devices.
\item
  \textbf{Scalability:} The backend (FastAPI) must support
  high-performance asynchronous requests for future user growth.
\item
  \textbf{Efficiency:} The ML model must be optimized (MobileNetV2 or
  ResNet-50) to have a small footprint suitable for mobile deployment.
\end{itemize}

